They were kept simple for the idea of performance, but really it would be better to just have a very informative manifest to enable smarter compilation that can have more performance gains than simple manifests alone.

They can even be minifed and "compiled" themselves.

E.g.
**some.js:**
// @require stuff.js
window.a = 1;

**someJs.manifest:**
{ require: 'core', stylesheets: ['shared', 'christmas-theme'] }

and then

**some.compiled.js**
window.a=1;

**some.compiled.manifest.js:**
{'p':['../../../core.js'],'sp':[],'s':[],'sp':['css/christmas-theme.css']}

